Once your `configTest` and `configOther` beans have been created, Spring knows that they&#39;re an `Impl` and can be autowired as either an `IOne` or `ITwo`. There&#39;s no way of altering this behaviour as Spring will always use as much type information as it can, not just the information that&#39;s available from the bean definition.

In your example, there&#39;s no apparent need for two separate instances of `Impl`. You could define a single `Impl` bean instead:

```
@Bean
public Impl implBean() {
    return new Impl();
}
```

This same instance can then be injected into `ServiceOne` as both an `IOne` and an `ITwo`.

If you absolutely need `IOne` and `ITwo` to be satisfied using separate beans, you&#39;ll either have to use qualifiers or split your `Impl` into two classes; one that implements `IOne` and one that implements `ITwo`.

