Check your imports - you probably have imported `java.util.function.Predicate`, which made the function&#39;s return type `java.util.function.Predicate`:

    private Predicate&lt;String&gt; paths() {
    //      ^^^^^^^^^
    // this is java.util.function.Predicate

[`Predicates.not`][1] returns a `com.google.common.base.Predicate`, hence the error.

You should first make up your mind about which type of predicate your method should return.

If you want it to return `com.google.common.base.Predicate`, change your import to:

    import com.google.common.base.Predicate;

If you want it to return `java.util.function.Predicate` (perhaps [because you want to use it in a stream][2] or otherwise), you can return the method reference to `apply`:

    return Predicates.not(PathSelectors.regex(&quot;/error&quot;))::apply;

&lt;hr&gt;

Since the regex `/error` just matches the string `/error` literally, you could also just do (assuming `PathSelectors` is `springfox.documentation.builders.PathSelectors`):

    return path -&gt; !path.equals(&quot;/error&quot;);

in this case, and this will work for both types of predicates.

On the other hand, you might have meant

    return path -&gt; !path.startsWith(&quot;/error&quot;);
    // or
    return path -&gt; !path.contains(&quot;/error&quot;);

which is not what your regex matches.

  [1]: https://guava.dev/releases/19.0/api/docs/com/google/common/base/Predicates.html#not(com.google.common.base.Predicate)
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/q/35701317/5133585

